const faqs = [
  { q: "Can I borrow against a painting without selling it?", a: "Potentially. An art-secured loan can provide liquidity while the owner retains the painting, subject to a security interest and agreed custody, insurance, inspection and movement conditions. Approval still depends on the borrower, the work, the evidence file and the proposed transaction." },
  { q: "How do lenders decide how much blue-chip art can support?", a: "There is no universal percentage. A lender estimates net recoverable value from relevant completed sales, adjusts for the specific work, deducts likely realisation costs and allows for time, market depth and uncertainty. It then applies its own advance, concentration and credit policy, so the result is normally below an optimistic asking, insurance or auction figure." },
  { q: "What counts as blue-chip art?", a: "“Blue-chip” generally describes artists and works with sustained recognition, recurring demand and an established resale market. It is not a legal classification or a guarantee of liquidity. The specific painting's period, medium, subject, quality, provenance, condition and buyer pool remain decisive." },
  { q: "Does a catalogue raisonné entry guarantee acceptance?", a: "No. A catalogue raisonné entry can materially support attribution because such projects aim to establish reliable lists and histories of an artist's authentic works. The lender will still review title, provenance, condition, market evidence and the authority and scope of the publication or archive." },
  { q: "Can a painting with gaps in provenance be used as collateral?", a: "Possibly, but the gaps must be explained and assessed. Missing periods can raise questions about authenticity, title, theft, restitution, consignment or lawful export, so additional records or specialist research may be required. An unresolved material risk may reduce the collateral assessment or make the work unacceptable." },
  { q: "Does restoration reduce a painting's lending value?", a: "Not automatically. Appropriate, well-documented treatment may preserve a work, while extensive, unstable or undisclosed intervention can reduce buyer confidence or increase costs. A current specialist condition report and treatment history are more useful than a simple statement that the painting has been “restored”." },
  { q: "Can I keep a pledged painting at home?", a: "Custody arrangements vary by lender and transaction. Some structures require specialist storage; others may permit continued display subject to approved insurance, security, environmental, inspection and movement controls. The arrangement should be agreed before the documents are signed." },
  { q: "What documents are usually needed for an art-backed loan?", a: "Typical documents include proof of ownership, a provenance chronology, catalogue raisonné or authentication material, high-resolution images, a current condition report, relevant sale evidence, insurance details and storage information. Corporate, trust, estate and identity documents may also be required depending on the owner and transaction." },
